3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC applies funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC for ENA/USDT perpetuals. The funding rate is calculated using a time-weighted average of the premium between the perpetual price and the spot index over the preceding 8-hour period. Traders holding long positions pay funding when rates are positive, while shorts receive payment, with the exchange taking no cut from funding transfers."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ENA","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA represents Ethena Protocol's governance token, making it sensitive to DeFi yield farming trends and stablecoin adoption cycles. MEXC's early listing advantage often creates temporary liquidity imbalances and funding rate premiums as other exchanges catch up with token availability."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA/USDT funding rates on MEXC have shown significant volatility since listing, with rates frequently exceeding ±0.3% during major DeFi narrative shifts. The token's connection to Ethena's synthetic dollar protocol creates funding rate spikes during stablecoin market stress or yield farming booms. Early trading periods often exhibited negative funding rates as shorts dominated, typical of newly listed DeFi tokens on MEXC. Monthly funding rate averages have ranged from -0.05% to +0.15% depending on broader DeFi market sentiment."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees create compelling arbitrage setups when ENA funding rates diverge significantly from competitors like Binance or OKX. Delta-neutral strategies become highly profitable when funding rate differentials exceed 0.1% between exchanges, especially given MEXC's 8-hour intervals. The exchange's thinner order books can amplify funding rate extremes during high volatility periods, creating short-term arbitrage windows. Cross-exchange arbitrage is most effective when combining MEXC's maker fee advantage with funding rate premiums during DeFi sector rotations."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's regulatory uncertainty and questionable volume reporting practices introduce counterparty risks that must be factored into funding rate strategies. The exchange's thinner liquidity for ENA can result in slippage during position adjustments, particularly for larger arbitrage sizes exceeding $50,000. Auto-deleveraging risks are higher on MEXC during extreme market conditions due to smaller insurance funds compared to tier-1 exchanges. Funding rate calculations may be less reliable during low-volume periods, potentially leading to unexpected rate reversals that can trap arbitrageurs."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How do MEXC's zero maker fees impact ENA funding rate arbitrage profitability?","answer":"Zero maker fees on MEXC significantly enhance arbitrage returns by eliminating trading costs when establishing delta-neutral positions. This fee advantage can add 0.02-0.06% to effective funding rate yields compared to exchanges charging standard maker fees."},{"question":"What makes ENA funding rates more volatile on MEXC compared to other exchanges?","answer":"MEXC's early listing strategy and smaller user base create thinner liquidity conditions that amplify funding rate swings. Additionally, the exchange's DeFi-focused user demographics tend to take more directional positions in tokens like ENA."},{"question":"Are there specific times when ENA funding rates on MEXC offer better arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Peak opportunities typically occur around major DeFi announcements, Ethena Protocol updates, or during broader stablecoin market volatility. Asian trading hours often see increased activity due to MEXC's user base concentration."},{"question":"How reliable are MEXC's funding rate calculations for ENA/USDT compared to tier-1 exchanges?","answer":"While MEXC follows standard funding rate formulas, their calculations can be less stable during low-volume periods due to thinner order books. Traders should monitor rate stability and cross-reference with multiple sources before executing large arbitrage positions."}]}]
